Chapter 7: The Conversational Workflow: From Discovery to Defense
7.1 Phase 1: Discovery & Baseline Establishment
The workflow begins with the agent anchoring the conversation in the user's reality. The goal is to establish the "Cost of Inaction" (COI).
System Prompt Instruction: "Begin by establishing the Status Quo. Do not ask 'What do you want to achieve?' Ask 'What happens if you do nothing?' Force the user to articulate the pain in financial terms."
Dialogue Example:
User: "We need a better search tool."
Agent: "Understood. If you keep your current search tool for another year, what is the cost? Are you losing productivity, paying high license fees for a legacy tool, or suffering from compliance fines due to lost documents?"
7.2 Phase 2: Logic Mapping & Impact Cascade
Once the problem is quantified, the agent moves to mapping the solution. It uses the Impact Cascade framework to link features to value.
System Prompt Instruction: "For every feature the user mentions, ask for the 'So What?' Trace it to a KPI. If they say 'AI Search,' you ask 'Does that reduce search time or improve search accuracy? And what is the value of accurate search—is it risk reduction or speed?'"
7.3 Phase 3: Quantification & TCO Analysis
Here, the agent performs the "math." It must ask about the "dark matter" of costs—the things usually left out of sales proposals.
System Prompt Instruction: "You must calculate TCO, not just License Cost. Ask about: Implementation fees, Training time, API usage costs, and the internal labor required to manage the new system. A CFO will spot these missing costs immediately.".1
7.4 Phase 4: The "Skeptic's Review" (Stress Testing)
Before finalizing the output, the agent switches modes to "Adversarial Review."
System Prompt Instruction: "Simulate the persona of a conservative CFO. Review the VDT you have just built. Identify the 3 assumptions with the highest sensitivity (i.e., if they are wrong, the deal collapses). Challenge the user on these assumptions. Ask: 'We are assuming a 50% adoption rate in Month 1. That is highly aggressive. Historical data suggests 20%. Should we model a more conservative ramp?'".6
Chapter 8: Technical Integration: Server-Driven UI and API Orchestration
8.1 The "Shadow Tool" Pattern
To enable the VMA to control the frontend UI of the ValueOS platform, we utilize a "Shadow Tool" or "Function Calling" pattern. The agent is defined with a set of tools that correspond to UI components.21
update_vdt_node(id, value, source): Updates a specific metric in the tree.
render_chart(type, data_series): Triggers the UI to display a specific chart (e.g., "Cash Flow Waterfall").
flag_risk(risk_type, description): Adds a warning banner to the UI.
The agent does not execute these tools in a Python environment; rather, it outputs the intent to call them as a structured JSON block. The ValueOS backend (orchestrator) intercepts these intents and updates the React/Frontend state accordingly.27
8.2 JSON Output Strategy
The prompt explicitly separates the conversational layer from the data layer.
Prompt Snippet:
"You must separate your conversational reasoning from your data modeling updates.
Consultative Layer: Natural language advice, questions, and synthesis.
Data Layer (Hidden): A JSON object adhering to the ValueModelSchema that updates the state of the Value Driver Tree. This block must be placed inside <data_update> tags at the end of your response."
This ensures that the user experiences a fluid conversation, while the system captures rigid, structured data for the business case.
8.3 Handling Multi-Modal Inputs
Future iterations of the VMA should support multi-modal inputs, allowing users to upload a PDF of an annual report or a screenshot of a dashboard. The prompt should include instructions for "Document Parsing" to extract baseline metrics directly from these artifacts, citing the document name in the provenance field.25
